Name.BusinessNameLine1: THE SOCIETY OF THE FOUR ARTS INC

IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: TO ENCOURAGE AND CULTIVATE A TASTE FOR MUSIC, LITERATURE, DANCE AND OTHER ARTS. TO GIVE OR CAUSE TO BE GIVEN IN THE PALM BEACHES AND ELSEWHERE OPERATIC OR DRAMATIC PRESENTATIONS, CONCERTS, LECTURES, EXHIBITIONS OF THE VISUAL ARTS, AND OTHER ENTERTAINMENTS. TO BRING INTO COMMUNICATION WITH EACH OTHER ALL THOSE WHO DESIRE TO ELEVATE THE STANDARD OF THE ARTS, AND TO PROMOTE AND CREATE THE ENJOYMENT OF THE ARTS. THE SOCIETY SERVED APPROX. 99,853 ATTENDEES, VISITORS TO ITS VARIOUS PROGRAMS.
IRS990.Description: ARTISTIC PROGRAMMING: ATTENDANCE 46,361. CONSISTS OF ART EXHIBITIONS, CONCERTS, FILMS, METROPOLITAN OPERA, LECTURES, CHILDREN'S PROGRAMS. EACH YEAR THE SOCIETY OF THE FOUR ARTS PRESENTS A FULL SEASON OF NOTABLE PROGRAMS IN EACH OF ITS FOUR DESIGNATED MISSION AREAS: MUSIC, DRAMA, LITERATURE AND THE VISUAL ARTS (PAINTING, SCULPTURE AND ARCHITECTURE). CONCERTS, USUALLY PRESENTED ON WEDNESDAY EVENINGS, AND SUNDAY AFTERNOONS, ATTRACT ENTHUSIASTIC AUDIENCES TO PROGRAMS BY THE WORLD'S LEADING MUSICIANS AND MUSICAL ENSEMBLES---SUCH AS THE ACADEMY OF ST. MARTINS-IN-THE-FIELDS; THE TOKyO STRING QUARTET, THE AMERICAN CHAMBER PLAYERS AND SOLOISTS FROM THE METROPOLITAN OPERA. RECENT ART EXHIBITIONS IN THE SOCIETY'S ESTER B. O'KEEFFEE GALLERY HAVE PRESENTED TREASURES FROM THE STATE DEPARTMENT'S ANTIQUES COLLECTION, ALABASTER MASTERPIECES FROM THE LONDON'S VICTORIA AND ALBERT MUSEUM, DECORATIVE ART AND SILVER FROM THE WINTERTHUR MUSEUM, AND MANY PRESENTATIONS OF PAINTING AND SCULPTURE. ART FILMS AND MEMORABLE HOLLYWOOD MOVIES ARE SHOWN ON FRIDAY AFTERNOON AND EVENINGS; EACH SEASON'S FULL SCHEDULE OF LIVE HDTV BROADCASTS FROM THE METROPOLITAN OPERA ARE OFFERED ON SATURDAYS. MANY EXHIBITIONS AND CONCERTS ARE ACCOMPANIED BY LECTURES AND GALLERY TALKS, AND THE SOCIETY'S MULTI-ACRE GARDENS---BOTANICAL DISPLAY GARDENS AND A TWO-ACRE SCULPTURE GARDEN---ARE OPEN TO THE PUBLIC YEAR-ROUND, FREE OF CHARGE.

Activity2.Description: main library/children's library: ATTENDANCE 60,616. SINCE THE TOWN OF PALM BEACH HAS NO PUBLIC LIBRARIES, THE SOCIETY'S TWO LIBRARIES--- THE KING LIBRARY FOR ADULTS AND A SEPARATE, SUPERBLY EQUIPPED CHILDREN'S LIBRARY, SERVE, IN EFFECT, AS THE TOWN'S "OFFICIAL" LIBRARIES. BOTH ARE OPEN TO THE PUBLIC AT NO CHARGE (ADULTS PAY A SMALL FEE FOR BORROWING PRIVILEGES), AND BOTH PRESENT A FULL SEASON'S SCHEDULE OF EVENTS: STORY HOURS FOR CHILDREN, PLUS CELEBRATIONS OF SPECIAL EVENTS LIKE NATIONAL FIRE PREVENTION WEEK, WHEN PALM BEACH'S FIRE TRUCKS AND FIREFIGHTERS VISIT THE CHILDREN'S LIBRARY; AUTHOR VISITS, BOOK SIGNINGS, POETRY READINGS, LECTURES, BOOK DISCUSSIONS AND OTHER EVENTS FOR ADULTS.

Activity3.Description: EDUCATION (CAMPUS ON THE LAKE): ATTENDANCE 4,586. FOUNDED IN 2000 WITH ONLY A FEW EVENTS AND ATTENDEES, THE SOCIETY'S CAMPUS ON THE LAKE EDUCATION PROGRAM NOW PRESENTS SCORES OF EVENTS EACH SEASON AND ATTRACTS MORE THAN 4,000 REGISTRANTS ANNUALLY. ITS PRESENTATIONS RANGE WIDELY IN SUBJECT MATTER: ONGOING CLASSES ON SHAKESPEARE, OPERA, LITERATURE AND ART; FIELD TRIPS TO ART BASEL MIAMI AND OTHER EVENTS; CLASSES IN WATERCOLOR PAINTING, SCULPTURE, COOKERY AND FLOWER ARRANGING; ONE TIME LECTURES ON A WIDE VARIETY OF SUBJECTS. DESIGNED TO ATTRACT A BROAD AUDIENCE, THE CAMPUS ON THE LAKE HAS WON WIDE PRAISE FOR THE VARIETY AND DEPTH OF ITS PROGRAMS.

ActivityOther.Description: GARDENS: FOUNDED IN THE 1930'S, WHEN MANY VISITORS AND NEW RESIDENTS WERE UNFAMILIAR WITH THE SUBTROPICAL FLORA OF SOUTH FLORIDA, THE FOUR ARTS GARDENS WERE DESIGNED TO DEMONSTRATE THE VARIETIES OF HORTICULTURE POSSIBLE IN THE REGION. THE HORTICULTURAL DISPLAY GARDENS FEATURE SEVEN SEPARATE SECTIONS RANGING FROM A CHINESE-STYLE WALLED GARDEN TO A FORMAL COLONIAL GARDEN TO A SPANISH GARDEN AGAINST A MEDITERRANEAN-REVIVAL FACADE AND SHOWCASING AN ANTIQUE SPANISH WELL. TOTALLY RESTORED AFTER BEING DESTROYED BY SUCCESSIVE HURRICANES IN 2004-2005, THE GARDENS ARE MAINTAINED BY THE GARDEN CLUB OF PALM BEACH. IMMEDIATELY ADJACENT, THE TWO-ACRE PHILIP HULITAR SCULPTURE GARDEN, WHICH UNDERWENT A $10-MILLION ENHANCEMENT AND REOPENED IN 2006, DISPLAYS AN ENCYCLOPEDIC COLLECTION OF AMERICAN AND INTERNATIONAL SCULPTURE AND FUNCTIONS AS A PUBLIC PARK FOR PALM BEACH, AS A FURTHER SHOWCASE FOR SUBTROPICAL HORTICULTURE, AS A SOCIAL GATHERING PLACE, AND AS A VENUE FOR CULTURAL EVENTS (BALLET FLORIDA PERFORMED ON ITS PLAZA AT THE GARDEN'S REOPENING EVENT). THE GARDENS ARE OPEN TO THE PUBLIC YEAR-ROUND.

Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.Explanation: THE SOCIETY OF FOUR ARTS COLLECTION INCLUDES PAINTINGS, SCULPTURES, GRAPHICS, CERAMICS, FURNITURE, AND OTHER ITEMS. IN CONFORMITY WITH THE PRACTICES FOLLOWED BY MANY MUSEUMS, COLLECTION ITEMS THAT ARE (A) HELD FOR PUBLIC EXHIBITION AND EDUCATION; (B) PROTECTED, CARED FOR AND PRESERVED; AND (C) SUBJECT TO A POLICY DESIGNATING THE PROCEEDS FROM ANY SALES OF COLLECTION ITEMS TO ACQUIRING OR PRESERVING OTHER COLLECTIONS, ARE NOT CAPITALIZED AND ARE NOT REPORTED IN THE STATEMENT OF FINANCIAL POSITION. THE SOCIETY HAS DEVELOPED POLICIES FOR THE STEWARDSHIP OF THE COLLECTION FOLLOWING THE GUIDELINES OF THE AMERICAN ASSOCIATION OF MUSEUMS. TO BE CONSIDERED FOR THE COLLECTION, THE ITEM SHOULD BE RELATED TO THE COLLECTION AS IT NOW EXISTS, THE ITEM SHOULD BE HIGH QUALITY, AND THE ITEM MUST BE APPROPRIATE TO THE EXISTING BODY OF WORK IN THE AREA TO BE PLACED. THE SOCIETY ALSO CONSIDERS THE SPECIAL REQUIREMENTS FOR STORAGE AND EXHIBITION. IF THE ITEM IS TO BE DONATED, THE DONOR SHALL ALSO BE WILLING TO MAKE AN UNRESTRICTED GIFT. TO BE CONSIDERED FOR SALE, THE SOCIETY MUST DETERMINE THAT IT IS UNABLE TO PROPERLY CARE FOR THE OBJECT, OR IT IS DETERMINED THAT THERE IS A MARKED DISCREPANCY BETWEEN THE COST OF THE CONSERVATION AND THE AESTHETIC, HISTORICAL, OR FINANCIAL VALUE OF THE OBJECT. OBJECTS OF MARKEDLY INFERIOR QUALITY, EITHER INTRINSICALLY OR RELATIVELY , IN COMPARISON WITH OTHER OBJECTS OF THE SAME TYPE IN THE COLLECTION, MAY BE CONSIDERED FOR SALE. ALSO, OBJECTS NOW DETERMINED TO LACK RELEVANCE TO THE COLLECTION MAY BE CONSIDERED FOR SALE. IN ANY SALE OR DISPOSAL OF COLLECTIONS ITEMS, THE APPROPRIATE LEVEL OF APPROVAL MUST BE OBTAINED AND THE PROCEEDS FROM THE SALE ARE DESIGNATED FOR ACQUISITION OR DIRECT CARE OF THE COLLECTION. THE FAIR VALUE OF THE COLLECTION OBJECTS ACQUIRED BY GIFT FOR WHICH THE SOCIETY CAN MAKE A REASONABLE ESTIMATE OR OBTAIN APPRAISALS ARE NOT REPORTED AS CONTRIBUTION REVENUE IN THE STATEMENT OF ACTIVITIES BECAUSE THE COLLECTION IS NOT CAPITALIZED. PROCEEDS FROM THE SALE OF COLLECTION ITEMS, IF ANY, ARE REPORTED AS AN INCREASE IN UNRESTRICTED NET ASSETS.
THE SCULPTURE GARDEN WITH WORKS OF ART BY INTERNATIONALLY KNOWN ARTISTS OPEN TO, AND FOR PUBLIC EXHIBITION, SEVEN DAYS A WEEK.

Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.ReturnReference: Description of Uncertain Tax Positions Under FIN 48:
Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.Explanation: The Society is a not-for-profit organization other than a private foundation. The Society qualifies as a not-for-profit organization under Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(3) since it is organized and operates exclusively for educational purposes. Internal Revenue Code Section 501(a) exempts the Society from income taxes and Internal Revenue Code Section 170(b)(1)(A)(VI) allows donors a deduction for contributions to the Society. On July 1, 2009, the Society adopted FASB ASC 740-10, Accounting for Uncertainty in Income Taxes. This pronouncement seeks to reduce the diversity in practice associated with certain aspects of measurement and recognition in accounting for income taxes. It prescribes a recognition threshold and measurement attribute for financial statement recognition and measurement of a tax position that an entity takes or expects to take in a tax return. An entity may only recognize or continue to recognize tax positions that meet a "more likely than not" threshold. The Society assesses its income tax positions based on management's evaluation of the facts, circumstances and information available at the reporting date. The Society uses the prescribed more likely than not threshold when making its assessment. At adoption, the Society did not record any cumulative effect adjustment, and the Society did not accrue any interest expense or penalties related to tax positions. There are currently no open Federal or State tax years under audit.
